Well, you know, it was in a crowd
of people, your name popped up.

253
00:28:00,017 --> 00:28:01,746
Tall fella?

254
00:28:01,819 --> 00:28:04,117
Yeah, yeah, that's the one.

255
00:28:05,823 --> 00:28:07,848
Harry Gropke.

256
00:28:07,925 --> 00:28:11,691
Harry went to Vegas, I think.
It must have been Harry.

257
00:28:11,762 --> 00:28:14,526
Yeah, yeah. Yeah, Harry.

258
00:28:14,599 --> 00:28:17,966
You know something?
I've known Harry for thirty years.

259
00:28:18,035 --> 00:28:21,095
- I haven't seen him in twenty-five.
- Yeah?

260
00:28:21,238 --> 00:28:25,868
"I adore attractive,
well-groomed educated women:

261
00:28:27,211 --> 00:28:29,839
"You mean,
making the church scene?

262
00:28:29,914 --> 00:28:33,215
"Forget it, Reverend:
I'm not resting!

263
00:28:40,992 --> 00:28:42,425
Here we are.

264
00:28:42,493 --> 00:28:44,757
No strangers in here!

265
00:28:44,829 --> 00:28:46,257
That's Dave.
He's staying upstairs.

266
00:28:46,450 --> 00:28:48,723
He's from Las Vegas.
Good friend of Harry Gropke's.

267
00:28:48,747 --> 00:28:51,833
- I've got business to discuss.
- Not now, Grace. Later.

268
00:28:51,902 --> 00:28:55,599
Where's Cookie's silver cigarette
case? It was here by my bed.

269
00:28:55,673 --> 00:28:58,972
- I see you got a scale.
- Weight Watchers. Measures food.

270
00:28:59,043 --> 00:29:00,635
Get it for me.

271
00:29:00,711 --> 00:29:05,546
Lou, you get back here. You've got
to push the blood back in my feet.

272
00:29:05,616 --> 00:29:07,550
I'll be right back.

273
00:29:08,853 --> 00:29:10,912
Lou, come back!

274
00:29:18,863 --> 00:29:20,660
Come in, come in.

275
00:29:34,712 --> 00:29:36,942
Would you close the blinds?

276
00:29:46,957 --> 00:29:49,585
I need a tablespoon.

277
00:29:53,164 --> 00:29:55,257
That's great. Thanks.

278
00:30:01,439 --> 00:30:03,498
Italian baby laxative.

279
00:30:04,842 --> 00:30:06,833
That's what it is.

280
00:30:18,622 --> 00:30:20,886
You like magic?

281
00:30:23,761 --> 00:30:26,855
Pass your hand over the scale.

282
00:30:26,931 --> 00:30:28,626
What?

283
00:30:28,699 --> 00:30:31,031
Come on! Go on! Do it.

284
00:30:32,803 --> 00:30:34,236
That's $2,000.

285
00:30:35,673 --> 00:30:37,470
Two thousand dollars?

286
00:30:40,878 --> 00:30:43,210
Okay, say abracadabra.

287
00:30:43,280 --> 00:30:46,215
- Come on.
- Come on, say it!

288
00:30:47,284 --> 00:30:48,911
Abracadabra.

289
00:30:55,426 --> 00:30:57,189
That's $4,000.

290
00:31:15,713 --> 00:31:18,341
Could you stash this
for me somewhere?

291
00:31:18,415 --> 00:31:21,043
- Jeez, I don't know.
- It's only for a couple hours.

292
00:31:26,290 --> 00:31:29,350
Look, you know the streets here.
Could you walk me?

293
00:31:29,426 --> 00:31:31,621
I can't leave Grace.

294
00:31:31,695 --> 00:31:34,061
Are you afraid?

295
00:31:34,131 --> 00:31:36,156
I've got a medical problem with her.

296
00:31:36,233 --> 00:31:38,463
- Are you a doctor?
- Doctor?

297
00:31:38,536 --> 00:31:42,996
There's something wrong with
the feet. The blood don't flow good.

298
00:31:43,073 --> 00:31:45,735
Why don't you tell me?
Come on.

299
00:31:45,810 --> 00:31:49,974
- Wait a minute.
- Chrissie, I got a job for ya!

300
00:31:53,184 --> 00:31:55,675
Got your fingers warmed up?

301
00:31:55,753 --> 00:31:59,689
This is not Grand Central Station.
What's wrong with you today?

302
00:31:59,757 --> 00:32:03,386
These people are going to help you.
Come on, Peppy, you're in the way.

303
00:32:03,460 --> 00:32:05,087
You're fired, Lou.

304
00:32:05,162 --> 00:32:07,630
Dave, this lady's got a
million things wrong with her.

305
00:32:07,698 --> 00:32:09,859
Get her out of here.

306
00:32:09,934 --> 00:32:14,769
This lady is almost a qualified
therapist in Nevada and Oklahoma.

307
00:32:14,839 --> 00:32:18,969
She trained in Saskatchewan, Canada,
in the art of Korean foot massage.

308
00:32:19,043 --> 00:32:22,308
If you leave me alone with her,
I'm gonna kill you, Lou.

309
00:32:22,379 --> 00:32:26,645
Will you listen for just once?
This is not medicine.

310
00:32:26,717 --> 00:32:30,448
I'm still a very important woman
in this town.

311
00:32:30,521 --> 00:32:33,490
I'm Cookie Pinza's widow.

312
00:32:34,525 --> 00:32:38,291
He used to deliver coffee
for Cookie.

313
00:32:41,332 --> 00:32:43,266
He's my servant.

314
00:32:43,334 --> 00:32:47,430
Do you know that your whole body
ends at the bottom of your feet?

315
00:32:47,504 --> 00:32:50,439
You think I am just poking
your feet.

316
00:32:50,507 --> 00:32:55,501
Well, when I touch this spot,
this is where your spine is.

317
00:32:55,579 --> 00:32:59,845
When I touch this spot,
this is where your tummy is.

318
00:32:59,984 --> 00:33:02,817
You work for that Grace?

319
00:33:02,887 --> 00:33:04,479
I help her out.

320
00:33:04,555 --> 00:33:06,682
She pays you?

321
00:33:06,757 --> 00:33:11,592
You're her fancy man?
Are you servicing her?

322
00:33:11,662 --> 00:33:13,391
Every now and then.

323
00:33:13,464 --> 00:33:16,592
Wow. To be your age
and still working at it.

324
00:33:16,667 --> 00:33:19,659
Mr. Stud! Mr. John!

325
00:33:19,737 --> 00:33:23,400
Well, I keep myself in trim.

326
00:33:23,474 --> 00:33:26,568
Monte Carlo!

327
00:33:26,644 --> 00:33:30,978
The old casino is very, very slow
and old-fashioned.

328
00:33:31,048 --> 00:33:33,949
Rococo elegance. But the new casino
is just like Vegas.

329
00:33:34,018 --> 00:33:35,212
Really?

330
00:33:35,286 --> 00:33:39,985
The croupiers are French, but the
dealers are American from Vegas.

331
00:33:41,892 --> 00:33:46,488
You get your license to learn how to
deal and the world opens up to you.

332
00:33:49,466 --> 00:33:54,130
It's not just cards, you know.
It's your future.

333
00:33:55,472 --> 00:33:58,339
I want you to concentrate.

334
00:33:58,409 --> 00:34:01,537
I hate you going back
to that oyster bar.

335
00:34:01,612 --> 00:34:03,876
The world should be your oyster.

336
00:34:05,182 --> 00:34:08,879
Well, I've got so much to learn.
I don't know how to count in French.

337
00:34:08,953 --> 00:34:10,045
I know...

338
00:34:15,092 --> 00:34:17,458
Do you think you could teach me?

339
00:34:17,528 --> 00:34:19,553
Better than that.

340
00:34:24,802 --> 00:34:27,430
If you'd only stop being afraid.

341
00:34:27,504 --> 00:34:30,098
Deal with courage.

342
00:34:30,174 --> 00:34:33,371
You're a little pearl
produced by that oyster bar.

343
00:34:35,479 --> 00:34:37,413
Say that in French.

344
00:34:58,936 --> 00:35:01,632
The name Capone
mean anything to you?

345
00:35:01,705 --> 00:35:04,173
Al Capone? The Godfather?

346
00:35:04,241 --> 00:35:07,142
Lucky Luciano, Dutch Schultz,
Meyer Lansky.

347
00:35:07,211 --> 00:35:09,145
Do you know them?

348
00:35:09,213 --> 00:35:11,875
You work for the people
who work for the people.

349
00:35:11,949 --> 00:35:14,474
I was taken a shine to.

350
00:35:14,551 --> 00:35:18,180
Pardon me, but you don't exactly
look like the "King of the Mobs."

351
00:35:19,289 --> 00:35:24,022
Well, a few wrong turns,
wrong affections, some mistakes.

352
00:35:25,696 --> 00:35:27,926
It's all shit now.

353
00:35:27,998 --> 00:35:31,399
It's a shame you never saw
Atlantic City when it had floy floy.

354
00:35:31,468 --> 00:35:34,596
Remember the song, "Flatfoot Floogie
with the Floy Floy"?

355
00:35:34,671 --> 00:35:37,765
Hep cat and zoot suit.
That was the floogie part.

356
00:35:37,841 --> 00:35:39,832
The floy floy.

357
00:35:39,910 --> 00:35:42,140
That was something special.

358
00:35:42,212 --> 00:35:45,579
Atlantic City had floy floy coming
out of its ears in those days.

359
00:35:46,984 --> 00:35:49,282
Now it's all so goddamn legal.

360
00:35:49,353 --> 00:35:51,719
Howard Johnson running a casino.

361
00:35:51,789 --> 00:35:54,986
Tutti-frutti ice cream
and craps don't mix.

362
00:35:55,059 --> 00:35:59,393
The only difference between
Christianity and Hare Krishna is...

363
00:35:59,463 --> 00:36:01,397
Hare Krishna is real.

364
00:36:01,465 --> 00:36:05,162
If Jesus was alive today,
he'd be very much into Hare Krishna.

365
00:36:05,235 --> 00:36:06,872
- Chrissie!
- Yeah?

366
00:36:07,104 --> 00:36:09,334
Do my sinuses again.

367
00:36:13,444 --> 00:36:15,378
- What language is that?
- French.

368
00:36:17,448 --> 00:36:19,109
Is it hard, French?

369
00:36:19,183 --> 00:36:21,981
It's the language
of international diplomacy.

370
00:36:28,192 --> 00:36:30,660
It's nice, French.

371
00:36:30,727 --> 00:36:32,695
Your husband's a real cutie!

372
00:36:32,763 --> 00:36:34,697
He's leaving tomorrow.

373
00:36:43,841 --> 00:36:46,071
Have you seen my wallet?

374
00:36:52,416 --> 00:36:54,407
I can't find my wallet.

375
00:36:56,120 --> 00:36:58,088
We go this way.

376
00:36:59,656 --> 00:37:02,124
Yes, it used to be beautiful...

377
00:37:02,192 --> 00:37:06,959
what with the rackets,
the whoring, guns.

378
00:37:07,030 --> 00:37:09,021
Sometimes...

379
00:37:09,099 --> 00:37:12,330
Sometimes things would happen,
I'd have to kill a few people.

380
00:37:12,402 --> 00:37:16,498
I'd feel bad for a while, but I'd
jump into the ocean, swim way out.

381
00:37:16,573 --> 00:37:20,134
Come back in feeling nice and clean,
start all over again.

382
00:37:21,812 --> 00:37:24,144
I never seen the Atlantic Ocean
till just now.

383
00:37:24,214 --> 00:37:26,682
The Atlantic Ocean
was something then.

384
00:37:28,152 --> 00:37:31,451
Yeah, you should've seen
the Atlantic Ocean in those days.

385
00:37:33,423 --> 00:37:35,050
Come on.

386
00:37:39,796 --> 00:37:41,559
There's your hotel.

387
00:37:41,632 --> 00:37:44,863
I could like it here.
You can breathe.

388
00:37:46,403 --> 00:37:49,167
They used to call Atlantic City
the lungs of Philadelphia.

389
00:37:52,009 --> 00:37:55,501
We stay long enough, we could be
the nose of Philadelphia.

390
00:38:01,518 --> 00:38:03,679
- What room?
- 307.

391
00:38:07,224 --> 00:38:09,818
Look, you go up alone.

392
00:38:09,893 --> 00:38:11,656
What do you mean?

393
00:38:11,728 --> 00:38:14,162
Just hand him this.
I'll wait outside.

394
00:38:14,231 --> 00:38:15,994
Ain't you comin' with me?

395
00:38:16,066 --> 00:38:19,695
I can't. Not the way I'm dressed.
I mean, you look sharp.

396
00:38:19,770 --> 00:38:21,704
You ain't trying to set me up.

397
00:38:21,772 --> 00:38:25,299
I'm trusting you.
I left a fortune in your apartment.

398
00:38:25,375 --> 00:38:29,191
Look, you just give him
the package.

399
00:38:29,379 --> 00:38:31,488
You wait for an envelope
with the money.

400
00:38:31,689 --> 00:38:33,948
There's another 100 for ya.

401
00:38:33,972 --> 00:38:35,808
Can't you do it?

402
00:38:43,627 --> 00:38:45,822
You better get yourself
some new clothes.

403
00:38:45,896 --> 00:38:48,262
Tomorrow. Floy floy.

404
00:38:49,199 --> 00:38:51,429
- 307?
- Right.

405
00:38:51,501 --> 00:38:53,560
I'll be up on the boardwalk.

406
00:39:21,498 --> 00:39:23,159
I got a...

407
00:39:31,875 --> 00:39:34,036
I've got a package from Dave.

408
00:39:37,147 --> 00:39:39,980
What, is medicare dealing now?
Come on in.

409
00:39:50,060 --> 00:39:51,994
Everybody in?

410
00:39:53,330 --> 00:39:54,922
Pair of fives.

411
00:40:03,640 --> 00:40:06,939
Fella here wants to talk to you.

412
00:40:31,702 --> 00:40:34,034
Hey, man, what's going on?

413
00:40:48,251 --> 00:40:51,687
We'd like you to keep it going
if you don't mind.

414
00:42:01,024 --> 00:42:04,790
There's a lot of other people
we gotta see first.

415
00:42:04,861 --> 00:42:07,591
The whole East Coast
is like the Sahara Desert.

416
00:42:07,664 --> 00:42:09,996
Every source is dried up.
You old "kocker" you.

417
00:42:10,066 --> 00:42:12,432
Tell me.
Where'd you get this stuff?

418
00:42:12,502 --> 00:42:13,992
Medicare.

419
00:42:15,572 --> 00:42:18,234
All right. I'm sorry,
I didn't mean to offend you.

420
00:42:18,308 --> 00:42:21,903
I'm trying to hold a game together.
I'm calling everywhere.

421
00:42:21,978 --> 00:42:23,673
Four G's.

422
00:42:24,948 --> 00:42:26,882
I know. Four G's.

423
00:42:29,052 --> 00:42:31,145
Tomorrow, huh?

424
00:43:02,152 --> 00:43:03,585
Lou Pascal?

425
00:43:08,725 --> 00:43:11,125
Buddy. Buddy O'Brien!

426
00:43:11,194 --> 00:43:14,357
That's me!
You're lookin' great, Lou.

427
00:43:14,431 --> 00:43:16,023
How you doir?

428
00:43:16,099 --> 00:43:18,567
Fine. I'm doin' perfect.

429
00:43:20,170 --> 00:43:23,833
It's good to see you, Buddy.
Oh, here. There we are.

430
00:43:23,907 --> 00:43:26,501
Hey, hey, not from you, I don't.

431
00:43:26,576 --> 00:43:30,239
Go on, take it.
It's a good time for me.

432
00:43:32,115 --> 00:43:34,140
Get in the chair.
I'll give you a shine.

433
00:43:48,331 --> 00:43:50,265
- It's a long time.
- Yeah.

434
00:43:52,936 --> 00:43:55,131
Remember the day
Nucky Johnson sent us...

435
00:43:55,205 --> 00:43:58,003
to buy 100 boxes of rubbers
for the party?

436
00:43:59,943 --> 00:44:01,877
The look the guy gave us!

437
00:44:01,945 --> 00:44:04,846
A hundred boxes of rubbers
for two guys.

438
00:44:04,915 --> 00:44:06,940
He couldn't get over it.

439
00:44:08,852 --> 00:44:11,013
Buddy, you live too much
in the past.

440
00:44:11,087 --> 00:44:14,488
Yeah. But them were the days.

441
00:44:57,801 --> 00:44:59,735
Mrs. Matthews?

442
00:44:59,803 --> 00:45:01,236
Yes.

443
00:45:02,472 --> 00:45:05,066
Great! Where did you find it?

444
00:45:10,146 --> 00:45:12,376
I have a vision of the future.

445
00:45:12,449 --> 00:45:15,350
This glorious island
of Atlantic City...

446
00:45:15,418 --> 00:45:19,286
shining like a beacon whose light
was nearly extinguished.

447
00:45:19,356 --> 00:45:23,383
If it wasn't for the casinos,
we'd have been dead a long time ago.

448
00:45:23,460 --> 00:45:27,055
And so I accept with great pleasure
this check from all the casinos.

449
00:45:27,130 --> 00:45:31,294
- Thank you, Mr. Goulet.
- You're welcome, Doctor.

450
00:45:31,368 --> 00:45:33,598
I want to thank the people
whose money I had for a while.

451
00:45:33,670 --> 00:45:36,298
Last night I was lucky at the tables
but on the way home...

452
00:45:36,373 --> 00:45:41,140
on the boardwalk,
I was mugged by my own croupier!

453
00:46:00,163 --> 00:46:04,031
# Just flew into town tonight

454
00:46:04,100 --> 00:46:07,501
# Lady Luck was on our flight

455
00:46:07,570 --> 00:46:09,504
# Had a bite to eat

456
00:46:09,572 --> 00:46:11,802
# At Geno's down the street

457
00:46:11,875 --> 00:46:15,675
# And now this welcome sight

458
00:46:15,745 --> 00:46:19,306
# Glad to see you're born again

459
00:46:19,382 --> 00:46:23,079
# Atlantic City, my old friend

460
00:46:23,153 --> 00:46:25,087
# Be there when I bet on ten

461
00:46:26,623 --> 00:46:29,290
You're not planning
on leaving town yourself, are you?

462
00:46:29,359 --> 00:46:32,726
I want to make it here. I really
like this town. I wanna be a dealer.

463
00:46:32,796 --> 00:46:35,321
I think Atlantic City's the greatest.

464
00:46:35,398 --> 00:46:37,559
- Mrs. Matthews, you...
- What?

465
00:46:37,634 --> 00:46:39,568
You can claim the body tomorrow.

466
00:46:39,636 --> 00:46:42,366
I don't want the body!

467
00:46:43,473 --> 00:46:47,204
# And now you're here to stay

468
00:46:47,277 --> 00:46:50,804
# Remember how they put you down

469
00:46:50,880 --> 00:46:54,976
# There's not an empty room in town

470
00:46:55,051 --> 00:46:58,020
# They're coming here
from miles around

471
00:46:58,088 --> 00:47:00,386
# You sure came through

472
00:47:03,426 --> 00:47:07,419
# I'm glad to see you're born again

473
00:47:07,497 --> 00:47:09,692
Saskatchewan. Area code 306...

474
00:47:14,437 --> 00:47:19,238
- To Mr. Or Mrs. Peter Matthews.
- # You're back upon the map again

475
00:47:19,309 --> 00:47:21,072
Sally Matthews.

476
00:47:21,144 --> 00:47:24,204
# You sure came through

477
00:47:24,280 --> 00:47:27,272
What do you mean they won't accept
the charges? It's about their son.

478
00:47:27,350 --> 00:47:30,080
Hello? Dave's dead. Hello!

479
00:47:38,161 --> 00:47:40,629
- I heard about Dave. I'm sorry.
- Who are...

480
00:47:40,697 --> 00:47:43,097
We live in the same building.
Next door.

481
00:47:45,135 --> 00:47:47,569
Come on, I'll walk you home.

482
00:47:49,639 --> 00:47:53,541
I don't know what to do about his
body. I tried calling his parents.

483
00:47:53,610 --> 00:47:55,544
They wouldn't even accept
the charges.

484
00:47:55,612 --> 00:47:59,343
- They've got to know.
- I don't have any money.

485
00:48:01,317 --> 00:48:03,444
Don't worry about it.
Come on.

486
00:48:18,768 --> 00:48:20,463
I can't. I, I...

487
00:48:23,139 --> 00:48:26,131
Hello? Mr. Matthews?

488
00:48:26,209 --> 00:48:29,508
I was a friend of your son Dave.

489
00:48:29,579 --> 00:48:32,980
My name... My name is Lou.

490
00:48:33,049 --> 00:48:37,748
I'm sorry to have to tell you.
There's been a very bad accident.

491
00:48:42,292 --> 00:48:44,351
Can I take your order?

492
00:48:44,427 --> 00:48:46,793
Just some water, please.

493
00:48:57,907 --> 00:49:01,206
The news didn't exactly break their
hearts, but at least they know.

494
00:49:04,547 --> 00:49:08,381
I've been thinking about
the burial and disposal.

495
00:49:09,452 --> 00:49:12,012
You're gonna need help.

496
00:49:12,088 --> 00:49:14,989
I hate to bring this up, but...

497
00:49:15,058 --> 00:49:17,322
when something like this happens...

498
00:49:17,393 --> 00:49:19,418
there's certain things
you've got to do.

499
00:49:19,495 --> 00:49:21,429
And you're new in this town.

500
00:49:22,732 --> 00:49:24,256
Christ!

501
00:49:31,007 --> 00:49:33,703
Remember, I'm Lou Pascal
if there's anything you need.

502
00:49:33,776 --> 00:49:36,506
I know your name from the mailbox.
I got a piece of your mail once.

503
00:49:36,579 --> 00:49:39,639
- I slipped it under your door.
- Oh, was that you?

504
00:49:39,716 --> 00:49:43,117
It was just junk mail,
but I appreciate what you did.

505
00:49:43,186 --> 00:49:46,019
Coupons for paper towels.
You saved me money.

506
00:49:48,157 --> 00:49:51,217
- I'm Sally Matthews.
- I know.

507
00:49:51,294 --> 00:49:54,024
Thanks very much
for everything, really.

508
00:49:54,097 --> 00:49:55,758
It's okay.

509
00:50:01,204 --> 00:50:03,695
God, I don't know
what to say to my sister.

510
00:50:05,842 --> 00:50:10,506
Look, your sister is downstairs
baby-sitting Grace... Mrs. Pinza.

511
00:50:10,580 --> 00:50:13,481
Why don't you go to bed, get
some rest, tell her in the morning?

512
00:50:13,549 --> 00:50:15,574
Young girls are strong.

513
00:50:15,652 --> 00:50:17,483
Yeah.

514
00:50:17,553 --> 00:50:21,379
Good night.

515
00:51:03,266 --> 00:51:04,699
Jesus.

516
00:53:09,659 --> 00:53:12,093
You can go upstairs now.

517
00:53:13,565 --> 00:53:15,465
All right, all right.

518
00:53:18,303 --> 00:53:19,895
Your sister is back.

519
00:54:16,928 --> 00:54:19,192
What's got into you?

520
00:56:00,598 --> 00:56:02,031
Shit!

521
00:56:03,534 --> 00:56:06,332
- Where are my oysters?
- Relax.

522
00:56:06,404 --> 00:56:09,464
Well, at least you got
your wallet back.

523
00:56:09,540 --> 00:56:14,034
Last night I dreamt I came here
and Dave's body was on the ice.

524
00:56:16,414 --> 00:56:18,575
- Sign this.
- What is it?

525
00:56:18,650 --> 00:56:21,710
It's for your husband.
Sign here and here.

526
00:56:21,786 --> 00:56:24,516
- But what...
- Believe me, it's all right.

527
00:56:24,589 --> 00:56:28,548
And put down the address,
the family address in Canada.

528
00:56:30,728 --> 00:56:33,595
- What did you do to your hand?
- Nothing.

529
00:56:34,966 --> 00:56:37,958
- What time do you get off?
- 12:00.

530
00:56:40,638 --> 00:56:43,368
Terrific. I'll see you.

531
00:57:12,470 --> 00:57:14,438
Holy shit!

532
00:57:14,505 --> 00:57:17,565
Santa Claus is looking real hot.
Come on in.

533
00:57:17,642 --> 00:57:21,840
Everybody, hold it. Let's have
a little applause for Santa Claus.

534
00:57:23,548 --> 00:57:24,981
Gentlemen.

535
00:57:25,883 --> 00:57:29,341
Go ahead.
Compliments of the house.

536
00:57:30,421 --> 00:57:34,357
Hey, Pops, what planet
do you come from?

537
00:57:34,425 --> 00:57:39,124
I want to do something for ya.
Here, take my watch. Go ahead.

538
00:57:40,598 --> 00:57:43,761
You don't want it? Take my wife!
Take my life! Take anything!

539
00:57:43,835 --> 00:57:46,702
Just cut out the bullshit.
Let me have the money.

540
00:57:51,509 --> 00:57:53,443
You're all right, Pops.

541
00:58:02,887 --> 00:58:05,219
Not bad. Not bad.

542
00:58:07,658 --> 00:58:11,355
Couple of inches off the sleeves,
a little off the skirt...

543
00:58:11,429 --> 00:58:13,397
and you'll look just fine.

544
00:58:14,465 --> 00:58:15,932
For the tailor.

545
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:19,993
Double sawbuck?
Hey, thanks a lot!

546
00:58:20,071 --> 00:58:23,131
Listen, when things start going good
for me, I'll make it up to you.

547
00:58:29,714 --> 00:58:32,274
A dozen oysters, please.

548
00:58:32,350 --> 00:58:34,944
- Hi.
- I took care of Dave.

549
00:58:35,019 --> 00:58:38,386
The forms you signed, they were
releases to send the body to Canada.

550
00:58:38,456 --> 00:58:43,086
You were busy, and the arrangements,
mail, the plane, it's a lot of work.

551
00:58:43,161 --> 00:58:46,062
You paid to have his body
flown to Canada?

552
00:58:46,130 --> 00:58:47,893
I hope you don't mind.

553
00:58:47,965 --> 00:58:52,629
- The money! Must've been expensive.
- Forget the money. I'm a neighbor.

554
00:58:54,172 --> 00:58:56,106
Why are you doing all this?

555
00:58:56,174 --> 00:58:59,234
It's nothing!
Sinatra gives wings to hospitals.

556
00:58:59,310 --> 00:59:01,710
We all do what we can.

557
00:59:01,779 --> 00:59:04,339
- It's 12:00.
- Yeah?

558
00:59:04,415 --> 00:59:06,406
I'll wait for you.

559
00:59:11,022 --> 00:59:13,183
There's four extra in there.

560
00:59:13,257 --> 00:59:16,454
They're really strict here. They
count the shells. I'm not kidding.

561
00:59:16,527 --> 00:59:19,655
I don't really want these, honey.
We're going to lunch.

562
00:59:19,730 --> 00:59:21,630
Hey, thanks!

563
00:59:31,309 --> 00:59:32,936
New casino.

564
00:59:33,010 --> 00:59:37,276
Burger King casinos. McDonald's
casinos. Pizzeria casinos. Jesus!

565
00:59:37,348 --> 00:59:40,010
Where I work they rake in
over a million bucks a day.

566
00:59:40,084 --> 00:59:42,075
- Really?
- Yeah.

567
00:59:45,690 --> 00:59:48,523
You like the casinos?
You go to them?

568
00:59:48,593 --> 00:59:51,221
No. No, I don't like them.

569
00:59:51,295 --> 00:59:54,321
They're too wholesome for me.

570
00:59:54,398 --> 00:59:58,528
I mean nuns, for Christ sake,
standing in line. Boy Scout troops.

571
00:59:58,603 --> 01:00:01,936
People blowing their...
their welfare checks.

572
01:00:02,006 --> 01:00:04,736
It's too much nickel-and-diming.

573
01:00:04,809 --> 01:00:08,438
All that money you carry around,
that's no nickel-and-diming.

574
01:00:08,513 --> 01:00:10,572
It quiets the nerves.

575
01:00:11,883 --> 01:00:16,320
Why do you live in the same dump
I do when you could afford a palace?

576
01:00:16,387 --> 01:00:17,820
Well, I...

577
01:00:19,957 --> 01:00:22,050
To tell you the truth,
I stay there for Grace.

578
01:00:22,126 --> 01:00:26,756
When they tear it down, I'll take
Grace someplace and head to Miami.

579
01:00:26,831 --> 01:00:28,264
You like Miami?

580
01:00:28,332 --> 01:00:30,926
I'm thinking of going to Monaco.

581
01:00:31,002 --> 01:00:32,594
Oh, Monaco!

582
01:00:32,670 --> 01:00:35,434
That's the place with that Kelly
girl from Philadelphia. She's queen.

583
01:00:35,506 --> 01:00:39,670
Yeah, they have a casino there,
very elegant.

584
01:00:39,744 --> 01:00:42,110
No women dealers yet,
but I'm hoping.

585
01:00:42,179 --> 01:00:46,582
Only now I'm learning about music
and I'm gonna start reading books.

586
01:00:46,651 --> 01:00:51,281
Developing some style. Learning new
languages because I want to travel.

587
01:00:51,355 --> 01:00:54,290
You thinking of leaving Atlantic City?

588
01:00:54,358 --> 01:00:56,792
Not for a couple of years.
I've got to develop my blackjack.

589
01:00:56,861 --> 01:01:00,160
I'm gonna deal my way to Europe,
to Monte Carlo.

590
01:01:01,265 --> 01:01:03,358
A regular Princess Grace!

591
01:01:13,844 --> 01:01:16,244
- Catch of the day?
- No fish!

592
01:01:16,314 --> 01:01:19,943
No clams, no mussels, no oysters,
no shrimp! I want meat!

593
01:01:20,017 --> 01:01:21,951
Lamb chops and pork chops
and liver.

594
01:01:22,019 --> 01:01:25,147
Bring us a menu.
And, waiter...

595
01:01:25,222 --> 01:01:26,814
More wine, the same.

596
01:01:28,392 --> 01:01:31,418
I don't want anything that swims.

597
01:01:31,495 --> 01:01:34,623
- Cigarette?
- Yeah. Oh, no. They're too strong.

598
01:01:34,699 --> 01:01:36,690
- Can I see that?
- Sure.

599
01:01:40,271 --> 01:01:42,762
It's nice to have money
to have things.

600
01:01:44,208 --> 01:01:49,009
This belonged to Grace's husband,
Cookie Pinza, a personal friend.

601
01:01:49,080 --> 01:01:51,844
Puligny-Montrachet 1966.

602
01:01:53,117 --> 01:01:54,982
Smell.

603
01:01:55,052 --> 01:01:57,816
Okay?

604
01:01:57,888 --> 01:01:59,446
I'll do it.

605
01:02:04,328 --> 01:02:06,159
Teach me stuff.

606
01:02:07,431 --> 01:02:09,831
Like what?

607
01:02:09,900 --> 01:02:11,834
What you know.

608
01:02:11,902 --> 01:02:14,462
- You want information or wisdom?
- Both.

609
01:02:16,841 --> 01:02:18,638
I'll think about it.

610
01:02:18,709 --> 01:02:23,078
The smartest man in the world was
on a quiz show winning everything.

611
01:02:23,147 --> 01:02:25,513
You know how they finally
tripped him up?

612
01:02:25,583 --> 01:02:29,781
He knew everything under the sun
except his Social Security number.

613
01:02:29,854 --> 01:02:31,822
He could have had the world.

614
01:02:31,889 --> 01:02:33,413
What's yours?

615
01:02:34,492 --> 01:02:37,461
I don't have
a Social Security number.

616
01:02:37,528 --> 01:02:39,860
Everybody's got
a Social Security number.

617
01:02:39,930 --> 01:02:42,023
You pay income tax?

618
01:02:44,035 --> 01:02:46,094
You still got your fingerprints?

619
01:02:46,170 --> 01:02:50,800
- Well, sure.
- Let me see. Oh, my God!

620
01:02:50,875 --> 01:02:53,070
- You don't have any fingerprints!
- What are you talking about?

621
01:02:53,144 --> 01:02:55,738
I got fingerprints.
I got lines...

622
01:03:04,789 --> 01:03:06,950
You wanna go back to Saskatchewan?

623
01:03:07,024 --> 01:03:08,821
I mean for the funeral.

624
01:03:08,893 --> 01:03:11,862
Look, I haven't been back there
for ten years.

625
01:03:11,929 --> 01:03:15,558
I'll stake you to a round-trip.
You can come right back.

626
01:03:15,633 --> 01:03:17,066
Thank you.

627
01:03:18,436 --> 01:03:21,872
Then you should send a tribute.
Make a nice impression.

628
01:03:21,939 --> 01:03:24,806
Let me tell you, never let them
badmouth you at a funeral.

629
01:03:27,078 --> 01:03:30,639
Miss, I want these roses,
all of them.

630
01:03:30,715 --> 01:03:32,148
- All of them?
- Yes.

631
01:03:32,216 --> 01:03:36,175
Make a nice big wreath, hmm?
A card?

632
01:03:36,253 --> 01:03:38,915
- Just over there.
- Thank you.

633
01:03:38,989 --> 01:03:40,854
How many are there?

634
01:03:40,925 --> 01:03:43,587
Six dozen.
Would you like them sent?

635
01:03:43,661 --> 01:03:46,824
Yeah.
To Moose Jaw, Saskatchewan.

636
01:03:46,897 --> 01:03:49,127
"Moose Jaw"?

637
01:03:49,200 --> 01:03:51,794
It's near Medicine Hat.

638
01:03:56,540 --> 01:04:00,340
"Business prevents my being with
you on this sad occasion. Sally."

639
01:04:00,411 --> 01:04:01,844
Okay?

640
01:04:02,646 --> 01:04:06,013
And miss, send flowers...
nice ones...

641
01:04:06,083 --> 01:04:09,143
"To Dave from Lou and the boys
in Atlantic City."

642
01:04:09,220 --> 01:04:10,881
- You got that?
- Yes.

643
01:04:10,955 --> 01:04:12,547
Keep the change.

644
01:04:12,623 --> 01:04:15,091
- Thank you.
- Shall we go?

645
01:04:15,159 --> 01:04:18,026
This is going to be the biggest
social event in Moose Jaw in years.

646
01:04:20,564 --> 01:04:23,465
I've got to go.

647
01:04:23,534 --> 01:04:25,900
- I hope I didn't...
- No, no, no.

648
01:04:25,970 --> 01:04:29,030
I've got friends waiting.
I should have told you.

649
01:04:29,106 --> 01:04:33,440
We're fixing up this house
I'm moving to... a new place.

650
01:04:35,880 --> 01:04:37,871
Can I see you later?

651
01:04:37,948 --> 01:04:40,416
I've got a class.

652
01:04:40,484 --> 01:04:42,418
Well, it was a nice lunch.

653
01:04:42,486 --> 01:04:44,351
Yeah. Thank you.

654
01:04:46,624 --> 01:04:49,252
- Thanks.
- See you.

655
01:05:05,276 --> 01:05:08,336
Why did they have to kill him?

656
01:05:08,412 --> 01:05:10,346
Let's get away from here.

657
01:05:14,218 --> 01:05:17,949
- Dave was a nice boy.
- He was a shit!

658
01:05:18,022 --> 01:05:20,149
But you married him.

659
01:05:20,224 --> 01:05:23,250
Look, you would marry anybody too
to get out of Saskatchewan.

660
01:05:24,628 --> 01:05:26,493
Don't be mad at me.

661
01:05:31,669 --> 01:05:34,900
I'm sorry.
I'm not mad at you.

662
01:05:34,972 --> 01:05:37,736
It's just...

663
01:05:37,808 --> 01:05:39,503
I'm late and everything.

664
01:05:39,577 --> 01:05:42,011
You want to go to your friends?
Come on, I'll take you.

665
01:05:47,518 --> 01:05:50,316
Okay, stop right here.
This is the place.

666
01:05:50,387 --> 01:05:52,753
See that kid on the roof?
He's in my class.

667
01:05:54,225 --> 01:05:55,920
Come on in.

668
01:05:57,728 --> 01:05:59,696
- Hi, Sally.
- I know I'm late.

669
01:06:02,933 --> 01:06:05,458
Bernie?
I'm sorry I'm late, really.

670
01:06:05,536 --> 01:06:08,505
I know I'm over two hours late.
Forgive me, okay?

671
01:06:08,572 --> 01:06:12,440
Lou, Bernie. Bernie, Lou.

672
01:06:12,509 --> 01:06:15,535
Come see my room.
It's great.

673
01:06:18,282 --> 01:06:20,216
This Bernie...
you living with him?

674
01:06:20,284 --> 01:06:23,947
There's ten of us living here.
We're all dealers, would-be dealers.

675
01:06:24,021 --> 01:06:28,219
- Bernie's baccarat.
- Fancy game with the shoe, huh?

676
01:06:28,292 --> 01:06:30,920
- Very elegant, Bernie.
- I'm elegant too.

677
01:06:33,130 --> 01:06:35,155
Oh, that's Agnes.
She's roulette.

678
01:06:44,909 --> 01:06:47,810
You learn never to split a ten.
A ten is dynamite with a two card...

679
01:06:47,878 --> 01:06:51,041
but after that
it can be your tragic flaw.

680
01:06:51,115 --> 01:06:53,606
But it's not just dealing the cards.

681
01:06:53,684 --> 01:06:58,178
You have to know how to surrender
and how to wash the deck...

682
01:06:58,255 --> 01:07:02,988
when to burn it, how to pluck chips,
share the box, stuff like that.

683
01:07:03,060 --> 01:07:05,756
- When do you take your test?
- Three weeks.

684
01:07:05,829 --> 01:07:08,923
- I'll be making $20,000 a year.
- No kidding.

685
01:07:08,999 --> 01:07:11,433
Yeah. 30,000 with tips
if I'm really good.

686
01:07:11,502 --> 01:07:14,437
Hey. I'm gonna hang on to you.

687
01:07:15,539 --> 01:07:16,972
Be a gigolo.

688
01:07:19,043 --> 01:07:20,943
What about Grace?

689
01:07:22,112 --> 01:07:24,672
She came down here during the war...
beauty contest.

690
01:07:24,748 --> 01:07:26,716
Oh, for Miss America?

691
01:07:26,784 --> 01:07:31,812
Nothing like that.
More like Miss Pinball Machine.

692
01:07:31,889 --> 01:07:35,347
She came, she needed protection.
I protected her.

693
01:07:35,426 --> 01:07:37,587
She was this teenager.

694
01:07:37,661 --> 01:07:40,061
You protected her for forty years?

695
01:07:40,130 --> 01:07:42,121
Well, she got married
along the way...

696
01:07:42,199 --> 01:07:44,793
Cookie Pinza.

697
01:07:44,868 --> 01:07:47,166
But I don't want
to talk about Grace.

698
01:07:53,644 --> 01:07:55,942
Do you love her?

699
01:07:56,013 --> 01:07:57,913
I watch you.

700
01:07:59,817 --> 01:08:02,809
The place where we live...
I watch you.

701
01:08:04,688 --> 01:08:07,213
- Through my window?
- You saw me?

702
01:08:08,993 --> 01:08:11,553
I figured maybe
somebody was there.

703
01:08:11,628 --> 01:08:13,323
Did you know it was me?

704
01:08:13,397 --> 01:08:18,164
You were just this guy
across the way.

705
01:08:18,235 --> 01:08:20,066
Why do you use lemons?

706
01:08:23,240 --> 01:08:25,834
The fish smell.
I'm embarrassed.

707
01:08:27,411 --> 01:08:30,778
I thought maybe it was for some
other reasons I didn't understand.

708
01:08:32,049 --> 01:08:36,315
I even went to a supermarket
to look at lemons.

709
01:08:38,088 --> 01:08:41,683
It's just to get the smell off.
It's nothing weird.

710
01:08:47,364 --> 01:08:50,629
What do you do
when you watch me?

711
01:08:50,701 --> 01:08:52,635
I look at you.

712
01:08:52,703 --> 01:08:57,197
You take off your blouse,
then you run the water.

713
01:08:57,274 --> 01:09:01,108
Then you take a bottle of gold
perfume and put it on the sink.

714
01:09:02,579 --> 01:09:05,548
Then you slice the lemons.

715
01:09:05,616 --> 01:09:08,278
You open a box of blue soap.

716
01:09:09,353 --> 01:09:12,550
You run your hands under the water
to feel the temperature.

717
01:09:14,391 --> 01:09:17,417
Then you take the soap
in your hands and...

718
01:10:47,718 --> 01:10:50,118
Are you Dave Matthews' wife?

719
01:10:50,187 --> 01:10:53,156
Look, are you a cop? I told you guys
I don't know anything about him.

720
01:10:53,223 --> 01:10:55,953
- Let's have a look in the bag.
- What are you talking about?

721
01:10:56,026 --> 01:10:59,223
- The lady said...
- Let go of him!

722
01:11:03,500 --> 01:11:06,401
Hey, you. Relax, old man.

723
01:11:06,470 --> 01:11:08,734
This is none of your business.
You don't want to get hurt.

724
01:12:02,526 --> 01:12:04,460
Are you all right?

725
01:12:15,038 --> 01:12:17,700
Maybe you should go lie down.

726
01:12:20,777 --> 01:12:22,938
I don't wanna lie down.

727
01:12:26,817 --> 01:12:28,910
I didn't protect you.

728
01:12:33,257 --> 01:12:37,216
Where the hell have you been?
Men were tearing the place apart.

729
01:12:37,294 --> 01:12:39,626
You go out,
you don't even tell me you're going.

730
01:12:41,665 --> 01:12:43,599
You okay?

731
01:12:44,801 --> 01:12:47,361
What the hell are you wearing?

732
01:12:48,372 --> 01:12:50,806
That girl buying your clothes now?

733
01:12:50,874 --> 01:12:54,776
Miss, I warn you.
Stay away from him.

734
01:12:55,879 --> 01:12:57,813
Oh, Christ.

735
01:12:57,881 --> 01:13:00,679
- Did he let that happen to you?
- I'm all right.

736
01:13:00,751 --> 01:13:02,719
You shut up, Grace,
you goddamned old lady.

737
01:13:02,786 --> 01:13:06,449
If I'm an old lady,
what does that make you?

738
01:13:06,523 --> 01:13:09,117
I'm her lover!

739
01:13:09,192 --> 01:13:12,719
You wanna know his nickname
in the old days? "Numb Nuts."

740
01:13:16,967 --> 01:13:20,494
Men had names like "Legs"
and "Bullets" and "Cookie."

741
01:13:20,570 --> 01:13:23,130
His was "Numb Nuts"!

742
01:13:25,842 --> 01:13:27,469
Lou, open this door.

743
01:13:27,544 --> 01:13:31,776
- I know you're hiding in there.
- Chrissie? Chrissie!

744
01:13:31,848 --> 01:13:35,579
- Oh, my God.
